🛡️ Enterprise Vulnerability Assessment using GVM (OpenVAS)

📌 Project Overview

This project demonstrates an enterprise-level vulnerability assessment system using Greenbone Vulnerability Management (GVM / OpenVAS).

The objective is to identify, analyze, and prioritize security vulnerabilities in a system before they can be exploited by attackers.



🎯 Objectives

* Perform vulnerability scanning on a target system
* Analyze detected vulnerabilities using CVE and CVSS scoring
* Understand risk severity and impact
* Generate professional security reports
* Demonstrate real-world security assessment workflow



 🧠 Concept
> Vulnerability assessment is the process of identifying weaknesses in a system that could be exploited by attackers.

GVM performs:

* Network scanning
* Service detection
* Vulnerability matching using CVE database
* Risk scoring using CVSS



⚙️ Tools & Technologies Used

* Kali Linux (VMware Environment)
* Greenbone Vulnerability Management
* PostgreSQL (Backend Database)
* Linux Terminal



 🏗️ System Architecture

```
User (Web Interface - GSAD)
        ↓
GVMD (Manager)
        ↓
OpenVAS Scanner
        ↓
NVT Feed (Vulnerability Tests)
        ↓
PostgreSQL Database
```

 🚀 Implementation Steps

🔹 1. Installation & Setup

* Installed Kali Linux on VMware
* Installed GVM using package manager
* Configured services:

  ```bash
  sudo gvm-setup
  sudo gvm-start
  ```

---

 🔹 2. Feed Update

Updated vulnerability database:

```bash
sudo greenbone-feed-sync --type all
```

---

🔹 3. Access Web Interface

```
https://127.0.0.1:9392
```

---

 🔹 4. Target Configuration

* Created target:

  * Host: Local/Test system
  * Port: Default

---

🔹 5. Scan Execution

* Created scan task using:

  * Full and Fast configuration
* Initiated vulnerability scan

---

 🔹 6. Report Generation

* Generated vulnerability report
* Exported results in PDF format

---

 📊 Results & Observations



 🔍 Key Findings

* Detected multiple vulnerabilities across services
* Vulnerabilities categorized as:

  * Low
  * Medium
  * High
  * Critical


📌 Example Observation

* Outdated service detected
* CVE associated with known exploit
* High CVSS score (≥ 7)

 ⚠ Risk Interpretation

| Severity | Meaning          |
| -------- | ---------------- |
| Critical | Immediate threat |
| High     | Exploitable      |
| Medium   | Moderate risk    |
| Low      | Informational    |


 💡 Insight

> Higher severity vulnerabilities indicate greater risk and must be prioritized for mitigation.


 🧠 Result Discussion

The scan results demonstrate how real-world systems may contain:

* Misconfigured services
* Outdated software versions
* Known exploitable vulnerabilities

GVM correlates detected services with global CVE databases, providing:

* Accurate vulnerability identification
* Risk-based prioritization
* Actionable remediation steps



